pullRequest.body:
Second part of #9781. This also includes a `PartialOrder` instance on Dyck words directly reflecting the tree bijection, that in turn allows a `positivity` extension for `firstReturn`.

```suggestion
  (range p.toList.length).findIdx fun i â†¦
    (p.toList.take (i + 1)).count U = (p.toList.take (i + 1)).count D
```

```suggestion
lemma firstReturn_pos (h : p â‰  0) : 0 < p.firstReturn := by
```
right? And everywhere else
Once you have applied the other comment, this lemma will be in a form that positivity understands. Could you write the corresponding positivity extension? Feel free to cargo-cult an existing one
In order to write such an extension I need a partial order on Dyck words. There appears to be no canonical such partial order.

`take_firstReturn_add_one` is not an assumption, so this is a bad lemma name. What about this instead?
```suggestion
lemma count_take_firstReturn_add_one (h : p.toList â‰  []) :
```
The full name would be something like
```suggestion
lemma count_take_firstReturn_add_one_U_eq_count_take_firstReturn_add_one_D (h : p.toList â‰  []) :
```
but that's too long to be memorable
Can you just return `0` if `p = 0`? In fact, do you think there is a reasonable choice of junk value for `DyckWord.drop` when the subword isn't balanced?

I've done the first modification, but I answer no to the second question; in order to preserve `p.take i + p.drop i = p` for all Dyck words and have both summands also Dyck words, if `p` is of the form `q` then one of `p.take i` and `p.drop i` must be empty and the other must be the whole word, and there is no preference for either choice.
WHy is `leftPart` denested but not `rightPart`? I find this confusing
This is the exact unambiguous inductive construction of Dyck words (see the last part of #9781).

I mean I understand this, but naming them `leftPart` and `rightPart` is misleading in that the reader might expect them to be exactly analogous while there is actually a difference between the two. Can you find better, less, symmetrical, names?
I should have answered all your queries.

```suggestion
lemma length_leftPart_lt (h : p.toList â‰  []) : (p.leftPart h).toList.length < p.toList.length := by
```

```suggestion
theorem semilength_leftPart_lt (h : p.toList â‰  []) : (p.leftPart h).semilength < p.semilength := by
```
This belongs earlier, to the `nest` API

```suggestion
lemma toList_ne_nil : p.toList â‰  [] â†” p â‰  0 := toList_eq_nil.ne
```

It's a bad idea to make `i` implicit here.
1. It's much easier to provide the proof of `(p.toList.take i).count U = (p.toList.take i).count D` if you know what `i` is
2. You don't want the user seeing `p.take ...` in the infoview (since proofs are ellipsed) and having to click through to find out what `i` is
Yeah, I eventually deemed that as a mistake. This will be reverted in the next commit.

Having `h : p â‰  0` instead of `h : p.toList â‰  []` means that you will need to provide the hypothesis when rewriting. In those cases where an hypothesis appears in the LHS, we pretend it's not an argument to the lemma and make other arguments explicit in consequence. Here this gives
```suggestion
lemma head_eq_U (p : DyckWord) (h) : p.toList.head h = U := by
```
Note that the `(h)` is an extra sign that Lean can infer `h` from the LHS
Same here

Can you have a simp lemma of the form `p + q = 0 â†” p = 0 âˆ§ q = 0` and a non-simp lemma of the form `p + q â‰  0 â†” p â‰  0 âˆ¨ q â‰  0`? Then you wouldn't need `nest_add_ne_empty`
```suggestion
```

```suggestion
lemma count_D_lt_count_U_of_lt_firstReturn {i : â„•} (hi : i < p.firstReturn) :
```

```suggestion
lemma firstReturn_nest_add : (p.nest + q).firstReturn = p.toList.length + 1 := by simp
```
also aybe we don't need that lemma at all as it's basically `firstReturn_add` + `firstReturn_nest`? Can you make sure simp proves it?
Okay, maybe you want this lemma because `p.nest + q` is a common idiom, but please make sure simp works

```suggestion
outside the `U, D` pair that `firstReturn` refers to. `outsidePart 0 = 0`. -/
```

```suggestion
theorem nest_insidePart_add_outsidePart : p.insidePart.nest + p.outsidePart = p := by
```
Can you deduce both lemmas from `p.insidePart.semilength + p.outsidePart.semilength + 1 = p.semilength`, which you itself can deduce from `p.insidePart.length + p.outsidePart.length + 2 = p.length`?
All done.
Actually can you prove `Subsingleton (AddUnits DyckWord)`? Then this lemma is just `add_eq_zero`
`add_eq_zero` requires `AddCommMonoid`, and Dyck word addition is not commutative.
I'm sure `add_eq_zero` can be generalised to `AddMonoid`. Can you do that?

That, unfortunately, **cannot be done** â€“ at least left-cancellativity is required (which Dyck words do satisfy). [This MSE answer](https://math.stackexchange.com/a/4535529/357390) gives a counterexample to `add_ne_zero` on arbitrary monoids as the free one on two generators quotiented by `ab=1`.
Mind writing the cancellative version then?
All done (including your comment below on `head_eq_U`/`getLast_eq_D`).
Can you generalise this lemma to be just after `add_eq_zero`?
See my reply to your previous comment.

```suggestion
  rw [p.getLast_eq_D, drop_one, this, p.head_eq_U]
```
That doesn't work; the `p â‰  0` hypotheses are then left as side goals.
That's because you haven't removed the `toList_ne_nil.mpr` in the statement of `getLast_eq_D`
Can we have an unnamespaced (but primed) version of these lemmas that's stated for `CancelMonoid`?
Please protect all these lemmas
Please open a preliminary PR for the material in this file

Either write the corresponding `positivity` extension or
```suggestion
-- TODO: `positivity` extension
include h in
lemma firstReturn_pos : 0 < p.firstReturn := by
```
All done.

```suggestion
theorem insidePart_nest_add : (p.nest + q).insidePart = p := by
```

```suggestion
theorem outsidePart_nest_add : (p.nest + q).outsidePart = q := by
```

```suggestion
def evalDyckWordFirstReturn : PositivityExt where eval {u Î±} _zÎ± _pÎ± e := do
```
Can you provide lemmas like `p.toList <:+ q.toList â†” p < q`, `0 < p â†” p â‰  0`, `p â‰¤ p + q`, ...? I suspect it might have to be a separate PR

I've probably added â€“ and changed â€“ enough in this PR; we can merge this in its current state and leave the extra ordering lemmas to the next and last PR in my plans, #9781 itself where I will add the tree bijection/relation to Catalan numbers.

(The order lemmas are not needed to show the bijection.)

Sure
